{
  "text": "The class C is a base class if it can be recognized in P, satisfiability of its formulas is in P, and the class is closed under isomorphisms w.r.t. variable names. We say C is clause defined if for every CNF-formula \u03d5 it holds: \u03d5 \u2208 C iff {C} \u2208 C for all clauses C from \u03d5. Gaspers and Szeider [CITATION_1] investigated a specific type of C-formulas, namely the clause-defined base classes C, and showed that for any such class C, the detection of weak C-backdoors is in FPT for input formulas in 3CNF. In the following we examine the parameterized enumeration complexity of the corresponding enumeration problems. They describe in [CITATION_2] Prop. 2 ] that a bounded search tree technique allows to solve the detection of weak C-backdoors in FPT time. This technique results into obtaining all minimal solutions in FPT time and after the usual sorting we can enumerate them in Total-FPT.",
  "citation_candidates": [
